Yes, this approach simulates what you can see in the web UI, if you 
build the job, and then select one of the discovered checkpoints from 
the drop-down list that appears (when checkpoints are available) under 
the job-control buttons.

There&#39;s another option, too: you can declare a &#39;Checkpoint&#39; bean inside 
your CXML which if present will be used. But you&#39;d probably only want to 
do that if you had some other system auto-generating CXML per launch; 
making such a change in place might be forgotten if you sometimes want 
to build that same CXML without resuming from a checkpoint.

- Gordon @ IA

